[BID 1S] Partner opens \S, promising an opening hand with at least five spades.
[BID 2D] You have 14 points and a strong \D suit, plenty to force to game. Bid your suit at the two level: this is game-forcing, promises 13 or more, and shows a real \D holding. There is no rush to raise spades yet — describe your hand first.
[BID 2S] Partner rebids \S, confirming a six-card suit. Now you have a known eight-card fit.
[BID 3S] With three-card support and the auction already forced to game, raise to \S. This agrees the trump suit and leaves room below game for either partner to show controls toward slam.
[BID 4D] Partner bids a new suit after the fit is set — that is a cue-bid, showing a control in \D (an ace or a shortness) and interest in more than game.
[BID 4H] You cue-bid in return, showing your own control in \H. You are cooperating in the slam search, letting partner read your outside cards.
[BID 4S] Partner signs off in game. With the controls not quite adding up to a safe slam, four is the right level, and you pass.
[show NS]Your 2\D first, then the delayed spade raise, painted the whole hand — a good diamond suit and genuine spade support. The cue-bids let both of you check for slam and settle sensibly in game. It rolled home with an overtrick for twelve tricks.
