{You are staring at a twenty-count with a self-supporting six-card major of your own, and partner has opened; when the two hands may hold every trick between them, how do you make certain before you leap all the way to the top?
[BID 1S] Your partner opens 1\S, showing an opening hand and at least five spades.
[BID 2H] Game-forcing. You bid your powerful six-card \H suit at the two level, promising 13 or more, though your real problem is that you may have far too much for mere game.
[BID 3S] Partner rebids the opening major, showing extra length and a strong hand.
[BID 4N] You take control with Roman Key Card Blackwood, asking for the five keycards, the four aces plus the trump king.
[BID 5H] Partner's answer accounts for all the keycards, so no ace is missing.
[BID 5N] With every keycard present, you press on with the king-ask, 5NT, hunting for the outside kings that would let you count a full thirteen tricks.
[BID 6H] Partner shows the \HK, the last card you needed to locate.
[BID 7N] You add it up. With all the keycards, the king you were missing now found, and your own long \H suit cashing, you can count thirteen tricks off the top and bid the grand slam in notrump.
[show NS]This is the payoff of asking in the right order: keycards first, then the king-ask, so that you commit to seven only once you can actually count all thirteen tricks rather than hoping for them. Every trick came home. A grand slam is never a guess; ask, locate the last vital card, count to thirteen, and only then bid it.}
